r="1" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="2" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="3" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-body><fo:table-row block-progression-dimension.minimum="14pt"><fo:table-cell text-align="start" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="center" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:page-number/></fo:block></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="end" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell></fo:table-row></fo:table-body></fo:table></fo:block></fo:static-content><fo:static-content flow-name="xsl-region-after-blank"><fo:block font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" margin-left="0pt"><fo:table table-layout="fixed" width="100%" border-top-width="0.5pt" border-top-style="solid" border-top-color="black"><fo:table-column column-number="1" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="2" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="3" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-body><fo:table-row block-progression-dimension.minimum="14pt"><fo:table-cell text-align="start" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="center" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:page-number/></fo:block></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="end" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell></fo:table-row></fo:table-body></fo:table></fo:block></fo:static-content><fo:flow flow-name="xsl-region-body" start-indent="4pc" end-indent="0pt"><fo:block id="d6e16"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block margin-left="0pt" font-size="24.8832pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.optimum="10pt" space-before.minimum="10pt * 0.8" space-before.maximum="10pt * 1.2" hyphenate="false" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt" hyphenation-character="-" hyphenation-push-character-count="2" hyphenation-remain-character-count="2">Preface</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This is much of my life's work regarding the non-Jew in <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>
			<fo:wrapper id="d6e20"><!--Torah--></fo:wrapper> from my own personal study. I would like to share what I've found for
			posterity. These answers were received from my sojourn in <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>. I
			think many of us ask questions yet many of us get bogged down and never find definitive
			answers, which demoralize many of us to the point of giving up or disbelief. I like to
			think this book will convey the things that are incumbent on every human-being to know.
			It would be a personal tragedy if I did not convey it for posterity.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">I will use Hebrew words and phrases to help convey the original wisdom in context. Any
			translations into English are my own unless stated otherwise. Transliterated words will
			be italicised. I try to use only original <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> words, but when I
			deviate, it will most likely be due to problems in English words and their understanding
			that I need to rectify. Translated words from their original Hebrew often come out as
			vulgar by translators today. I do my best to not be common in my language. There is a
			balance that must be met between stooping language down for the simple man to understand
			and between giving the unadulterated wisdom. I think that balance is to use
			transliterated Hebrew nouns at the very least. If you're reading this book, then that
			means you must have the aptitude to learn new ideas and new words. We then might as well
			learn actual Hebrew words in context, rather than a translation that usually bastardizes
			the original meaning and wisdom of the word and any other negative side-effects a
			non-Hebrew language would do to describe Hebraic ideas and concepts. So consider these
			transliterations as an opportunity and a challenge.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">For most of the book, I'll be using the term <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline> instead of
			"Jews", which is the Hebrew translation for <fo:inline font-style="italic">children of Israel</fo:inline>.
			It's common today to refer to <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline> as "Jews" or the Jewish
			People, but for the sake of clarity, I'll be using <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>
			instead, which is usually the phrase used in <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This book will not be received well by many people. They will disagree with the book, but be
			unable to give a clear proof why, or at the least, give straw-man arguments. An example,
			would be arguing I'm wrong about the attributes I give to the word <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
				Noach</fo:inline>, when really, the arguer is referring to
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">goyim</fo:inline>. Unfortunately for them and their listeners, <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
				Noach</fo:inline> and <fo:inline font-style="italic">goyim</fo:inline> are two different
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline>/categories of non-Jews. It's comparing apples and
			oranges, as explained later in the book. Many do not understand the
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline> of non-Jews within Torah and it leads many astray and
			has caused much contention in the world. This book helps to rectify that. If I give my
			opinion about a matter, I usually preface the statement with "It appears to me" or "In
			my opinion". I also ask questions that I would like to know answers to. Please contact
			me through email.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This book is organic and being updated regularly. Instead of having a number of editions, I
			will be using a version number, similar to that of computer software and only use
			numbered editions when printing. The source files for the book are housed in a version
			controlled repository that is constantly being added to, updated, fixed and processed
			into multiple media formats.</fo:block>
	</fo:flow></fo:page-sequence>
