 Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block margin-left="0pt"><fo:block font-size="24.8832pt" font-weight="bold"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.optimum="10pt" space-before.minimum="10pt * 0.8" space-before.maximum="10pt * 1.2" hyphenate="false" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt" hyphenation-character="-" hyphenation-push-character-count="2" hyphenation-remain-character-count="2">Chapter 1. Introduction</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
    
    <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">This book is out to rectify injustices done from impure speech; particularly in the usage
        of the categories of non-Jews within Jewish Law: the <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>. This book
        will help to re-humanize the non-Jew within the <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> by clarifying
        proper terms used for non-Jews and their respective laws that unfortunately get convoluted
        and overlooked. There is a vicious cycle of de-humanization between the Jew and non-Jew that
        can be stopped by using pure speech and logical application of that speech to proper
        definitions within <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> has never been the
        problem. Rather, misunderstandings of different types of non-Jews is the main problem in
        this regard. Many today don't even realize there are different types of non-Jews in
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>, each with their own treatment. Specifically, this book is
        about subsets of non-Jews, their critical definitions, and <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> law
        pertaining to their respective non-Jew subsets. These subsets are either entirely mutually
        exclusive, or have only some exclusivity in respect to their properties. For instance, all
        humans have chromosomes, but not all humans keep kosher; so the subsets are defined in
        respect to the properties wrote about in this book. This book is about specific subsets of
        non-Jews and their respective properties. These subsets or categories, are called
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline> in Hebrew.</fo:block>
    <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Once the reader sees the different <fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline>			<fo:wrapper id="d6e51"><!--gedarim--></fo:wrapper> of non-Jews within
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> using their proper Hebrew nouns as described in this book,
        the reader will be able to see the improper usage of terms about the different non-Jews and
        how such terms lead to misunderstanding and misapplication of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>
        law, foundational misquotes used for antisemitism, etc. An example, is a translation and
        misquote of a major redactor of Jewish Law known as the R"AMBAM which says in his
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">Mishneh Torah</fo:inline> that a non-Jew who involves himself in
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> study is obligated to die.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
                <fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline>R"AMBAM, Mishneh Torah, [Hilchot Melachim 10:9]</fo:block>
        </fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> Such a translation and misquote that depicts <fo:inline font-weight="bold">all</fo:inline> non-Jews not only sounds horrible, it's actually wrong. In reality, as I
        shall prove in this book, the verse in the original Hebrew is describing <fo:inline font-weight="bold">wicked</fo:inline> non-Jews, who for the most part in our western culture
        today, don't exist. Unfortunately, the aforementioned translation is the common translation
        of such verses of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> law pertaining to non-Jews. Such translations
        and traditions about the non-Jew promulgate within the unlearned Jewish community and
        eventually end up in the non-Jewish community where the damage comes full circle.
        Thankfully, with proper understanding, this grave misunderstanding can be remedied. With
        this book, I hope to bring to light this proper understanding and will help usher in the
        true view of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> being a pleasant and peaceful path.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
            <fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline>"Her ways are pleasant ways, and all her paths are peace." - Proverbs 3:17</fo:block>
        </fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
    <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Gedarim</fo:inline> have certain properties associated with them. For instance,
        let's look at the word <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>. The <fo:inline font-style="italic">geder</fo:inline> for
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> has a legal status such that a <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> that
        gives <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedakah</fo:inline>/charity to <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>/a child of
        Israel(colloquially: a Jew): <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>
        <fo:inline font-weight="bold">cannot</fo:inline> benefit from that <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedakah</fo:inline> and
        the <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedakah</fo:inline> must be given instead to the <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>
        poor. However, when a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline>/a child of Noah(which is under a
        different <fo:inline font-style="italic">geder</fo:inline> than <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>) gives charity to
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>, the poor of <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>
        <fo:inline font-weight="bold">can</fo:inline> use that <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedakah</fo:inline>. Even more so,
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yisrael</fo:inline> has a <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvah</fo:inline>/commandment to save the
        life of a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> in trouble, while <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>
        have no such <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvah</fo:inline> to save the life of a <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>.
        Even more so, <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline> are obligated to not save a
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> from death. So then, one must ask: What is a
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>? What is a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline>? Why are they treated
        differently?</fo:block>
    <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">These different categories of non-Jews will be explained in this book. This book will
        properly show some correct definitions and differences of these <fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline>
        of non-Jews, which will expose many horrible translations or misunderstandings about quotes
        of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>. This book will help break the vicious cycle of ignorance by
        bringing back purity of language, which will help bring pleasantness and peace.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
            <fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline>"For then I will restore to the peoples a pure language, That they all may call on
                    <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>, To serve Him with one accord." - Zephaniah
                3:9</fo:block>
        </fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> The R"AMBAM in his Mishneh Torah, Hilchot Melachim 10:10, shows a good example
        of two different <fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">4</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
            <fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">4</fo:inline>"A <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> that wants to do a
                <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvah</fo:inline>/commandment from the other <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvot</fo:inline>
                of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>(beyond the seven of <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
                    Noach</fo:inline>) in order to receive reward, [<fo:inline font-style="italic">Yisrael</fo:inline>]
                does not keep him from doing it properly. And if he brings a burnt offering, we
                receive it. If he gives <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedakah</fo:inline>, we receive it from him and it
                appears to me that it is given to the poor of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yisrael</fo:inline>. He
                receives his sustenance from <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yisrael</fo:inline> and it is a
                    <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvah</fo:inline> to sustain his life. However, the
                    <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> that gives <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedakah</fo:inline>, we receive it
                and give it to the poor <fo:inline font-style="italic">goyim</fo:inline>" - R"AMBAM, Mishneh Torah,
                Hilchot Melachim 10:10</fo:block>
        </fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote>Many will tell you that the <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> and the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben
            Noach</fo:inline> are the same thing: that they're all the <fo:inline font-style="italic">gentile</fo:inline>
        or the non-Jew in <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>; this is often how <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> is
        erroneously translated from the Hebrew into "gentile". However, as one can see, they are
            <fo:inline font-weight="bold">not</fo:inline> the same. There is some mutual exclusivity, as we
        just read, between the <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> and the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> who
        gives <fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedakah</fo:inline>. Even though both <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> and
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> are in the set of non-Jews, they are their own respective
        subset with their own respective properties and <fo:inline font-style="italic">dinim</fo:inline>/laws. These sets
        or categories are called <fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline> and it is these sets and their
        respective properties which is what this book is about. Before we get into the different
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">gedarim</fo:inline>, let's first learn a few definitions that are mandatory for
        this book.</fo:block>
    <fo:block id="d6e132"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Ikkar</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Ikkar</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
    <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">A great word to know is the Hebrew word <fo:inline font-style="italic">Ikkar</fo:inline>, which means concept or
            principal. In the southern United States, people say, "Bless his heart..." in regards to
            someone who tries to do right, but often fails by his or her own fault. "Bless his
            heart..." is an <fo:inline font-style="italic">ikkar</fo:inline> term. The phrase has meaning more than just
            the sum of it's parts, as it relates a concept. The <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> has it's
            own <fo:inline font-style="italic">ikkar</fo:inline> terms in which an <fo:inline font-style="italic">ikkar</fo:inline> term carries
            the same meaning from context to context, creating a continuity between these contexts
            that would otherwise seemingly not exist. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Ikkar</fo:inline> terms such as
                <fo:inline font-style="italic">Umot haOlam</fo:inline>/People of the World, <fo:inline font-style="italic">Chasidei Umot
                haOlam</fo:inline>/Pious people of the World, <fo:inline font-style="italic">Am haAretz</fo:inline>/people
            of the land, etc. are used throughout this book.</fo:block>
    </fo:block><fo:block id="d6e144"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Klipah</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Klipah</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>

        

        <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Before we go further, we first need to talk about souls and where they emanate from.
                <fo:inline font-style="italic">Klipah</fo:inline><fo:wrapper id="d6e148"><!--klipah--></fo:wrapper> is the Hebrew word for shell; a shell or rind of a fruit, for instance.
            Just as <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipah</fo:inline> blocks one from getting to the good fruit inside, so
            too, <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipah</fo:inline> blocks Godliness from being seen in this world. There
            are four major kinds of <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipah</fo:inline>. There are three completely impure
            and opaque <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipot</fo:inline> called <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipat tameyut</fo:inline> that
            does not allow any Godliness to shine through it. There is a fourth
                <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipah</fo:inline> which is a mixture of pure and impure called
                <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipat nogah</fo:inline>, which is an illuminating shell.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">5</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
                <fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">5</fo:inline>Tanya, Ch. 1</fo:block>
            </fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> It is not opaque, but translucent and allows Godliness to shine through
            it.</fo:block>
        <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Every living thing with blood in its body has an animal soul called a <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh
            behemut</fo:inline> and every human being has an additional Godly soul called a
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline>. The <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh behamut</fo:inline> emanates
            from the <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipot</fo:inline>. The <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline> is truly a
            part of <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>. Everyone can detect their <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh
                behemut</fo:inline>, but not everyone can detect, or is ruled by, their
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline>. All <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefeshot behemut</fo:inline>
            emanate from some type of <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipah</fo:inline> depending on what type of
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh behemut</fo:inline> it has. Unlike the <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh
                behemut</fo:inline> that emanates from <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipah</fo:inline>, the
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline> emanates completely, and is directly a part of,
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
        <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">While there is only one <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline>, there are two major kinds
            of <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefashot behemot</fo:inline>. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Umot haOlam</fo:inline> have
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefashot behemot</fo:inline> that emanate from the three, completely
            impure, <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipot tameyut</fo:inline>. Because <fo:inline font-style="italic">Umot haOlam</fo:inline>
            emanate from the completely impure <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipat tameyut</fo:inline>, people that have
            these animal souls do not detect Godliness on their own and therefore are seemingly
            completely removed from their <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline>/Godly soul.</fo:block>
        <fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">All human beings have a Godly soul called a <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline>. The
            <fo:inline font-style="italic">nefesh Elokit</fo:inline> is completely concealed in the <fo:inline font-style="italic">Umot
                haOlam</fo:inline> from their perspective. It hovers over them and is distant from
            them as what is called <fo:inline font-style="italic">makif rachok</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">6</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
                <fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">6</fo:inline>Ginsburgh, Kabbalah and Meditation for the Nations, page 55-56</fo:block>
            </fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
    </fo:block>
</fo:flow></fo:page-sequence>
	
    
    
