olumn column-number="1" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="2" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="3" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-body><fo:table-row block-progression-dimension.minimum="14pt"><fo:table-cell text-align="start" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="center" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:page-number/></fo:block></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="end" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell></fo:table-row></fo:table-body></fo:table></fo:block></fo:static-content><fo:static-content flow-name="xsl-region-after-blank"><fo:block font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" margin-left="0pt"><fo:table table-layout="fixed" width="100%" border-top-width="0.5pt" border-top-style="solid" border-top-color="black"><fo:table-column column-number="1" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="2" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-column column-number="3" column-width="proportional-column-width(1)"/><fo:table-body><fo:table-row block-progression-dimension.minimum="14pt"><fo:table-cell text-align="start" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="center" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:page-number/></fo:block></fo:block></fo:table-cell><fo:table-cell text-align="end" display-align="after" relative-align="baseline"><fo:block><fo:block/></fo:block></fo:table-cell></fo:table-row></fo:table-body></fo:table></fo:block></fo:static-content><fo:flow flow-name="xsl-region-body" start-indent="4pc" end-indent="0pt"><fo:block id="bnei_noach"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block margin-left="0pt"><fo:block font-size="24.8832pt" font-weight="bold"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.optimum="10pt" space-before.minimum="10pt * 0.8" space-before.maximum="10pt * 1.2" hyphenate="false" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt" hyphenation-character="-" hyphenation-push-character-count="2" hyphenation-remain-character-count="2">Chapter 4. Children of Noah</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block space-before="0.5em" font-style="italic" font-size="14.4pt" font-weight="bold">בני נח - Bnei Noach</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
	
	
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> are also <fo:inline font-style="italic">Umot haOlam.</fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">7</fo:inline></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Avraham</fo:inline> had the <fo:inline font-style="italic">din</fo:inline> of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Ben
			Noach</fo:inline>,<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline>Likutei Sichot, Volume 5, page 157?(see Rabbi Turen's audio. It says
				explicitly)</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> yet, he kept the whole <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline>, even its minutiae.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline>Talmud Bavli, Misechet Yoma 28</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> does not literally refer to children of Noah, like you would
		refer to the relationship in an ancestral way. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> is a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">madregah</fo:inline>/spiritual level that was considered <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzuveh
			v'oseh</fo:inline>/commanded and does in the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot Bnei
			Noach</fo:inline> before non-Jews stopped keeping the seven, which was also before the
		giving of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> at <fo:inline font-style="italic">Har Sinai</fo:inline>/Mount Sinai. Even
		non-Jews before <fo:inline font-style="italic">Noach</fo:inline>/Noah were called <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline>,
		so therefore <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> can't logically be literal descendants of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Noach</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline>Talmud Bavli, Zvachim 116a</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> Once <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> stopped keeping the seven,
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> loosed them from being
		<fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzuveh</fo:inline>/commanded. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> were at this
		previous time <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzuveh v'oseh</fo:inline>/commanded and does, in the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitvot bnei Noach</fo:inline>/seven commandments given to the children of
		Noah. However, because <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> were commanded but did not do,
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> loosed <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> from being
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzuveh</fo:inline>/commanded.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">4</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">4</fo:inline>Talmud Bavli, Avodah Zarah 2b and Bava Kamma 38a</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote><fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> after the giving of the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah</fo:inline> and till today are referred to as <fo:inline font-style="italic">lo mitzuveh
			v'oseh</fo:inline>/not commanded and does.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">5</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">5</fo:inline>Hilchot Melachim 8:10-11</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> It's highly important to note this change in definition. Non-Jews that are
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzuveh v'oseh</fo:inline>/commanded and does the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei
			Noach</fo:inline> today are called <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Ger
			toshav</fo:inline> is someone who does the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei Noach</fo:inline>
		because <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torat Moshe</fo:inline> the Torah of Moses says so, not because they think
		they're solely just moral laws, which would be like someone who is <fo:inline font-style="italic">lo mitzuveh
			v'oseh</fo:inline>/not commanded and does. It should also be noted that someone who is
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">lo'mitzuveh v'lo oseh</fo:inline> is called a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">6</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">6</fo:inline>R"ITVA, Makkot 9a</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Talk about the different stages of marriage. What stage is significant and where is the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">kavanah</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Talk about the <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yafat Toar</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Talk about how <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> are like women in Torah. They may are
		expected to do negative commandments, but not expected to do positive commandments. Negative
		Commandments are passive and not active. Negative commandments stem from the fear of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">
		<fo:inline font-style="italic">Yisrael</fo:inline> is a priestly nation. A priest is not a priest without those to
		intercede for. A king is not a king without a queen.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">A bride must be pure. The <fo:inline font-style="italic">Shechinah</fo:inline> cannot dwell with impurity.
		Keeping the <fo:inline font-style="italic">seven mitzvot bnei Noach</fo:inline> purifies the midot of a
		person.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">There is an arousal from above, which is the first time <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Yisrael</fo:inline>
		comes to the <fo:inline font-style="italic">yafat toar</fo:inline> in her impurity. He cannot be with her again
		until she is pure, which she must do herself: that is an arousal from below where she
		accepts to be a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> or a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>. The
		receiver is feminine and the giver is masculine: much like intercourse.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> are the children of Noah. <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem
			Elokim</fo:inline> commanded all <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> to keep the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei Noach</fo:inline>. The rainbow is a sign of that covenant.
		It's an eternal covenant. As long as a society keeps to the covenant, <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem
			Elokim</fo:inline> will not destroy that society.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">All of humanity are <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline>. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Yisrael</fo:inline> has
		a distinction from the merit of Avraham and are not classified as <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
			Noach</fo:inline> even though technically they are also descended from Noah.
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Goyim</fo:inline>, even though technically still <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
			Noach</fo:inline>, are idolaters.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">7</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">7</fo:inline>Nedarim 31a</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">It appears to me, that just as <fo:inline font-style="italic">minim</fo:inline> are still <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
			Yisrael</fo:inline>, <fo:inline font-style="italic">goyim</fo:inline> are still <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
		Noach</fo:inline>. But just like <fo:inline font-style="italic">minim</fo:inline> have special
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">halachot</fo:inline> they must follow as exceptions and be treated as an
		exception, so to <fo:inline font-style="italic">goyim</fo:inline> must follow exceptions and be treated as an
		exception. A <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> is to <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> as a
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">min</fo:inline> is to <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Therefore, whenever the term <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> is used, this is referring to
		those that are not <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>. I currently do not know if
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">gerim</fo:inline> are <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline>. I don't think they are,
		since a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> is no longer a part of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">amim</fo:inline>
		per L"S, Mishpatim Beis footnote 74-ish. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Gerim</fo:inline> are attached to
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline> and are described as being part of <fo:inline font-style="italic">klal
			Yisrael</fo:inline>. It appears to me that <fo:inline font-style="italic">gerim</fo:inline> would then also be
		from the merit of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Avraham</fo:inline> and set apart with with <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
			Yisrael</fo:inline> as <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Avraham</fo:inline>.<fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">7</fo:inline> This may only be when a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> circumcises
		himself that he becomes <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Avraham</fo:inline> and able to eat of the lamb of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Pesach</fo:inline>. See also Divine Providence in Derech haShem where it talks
		about grafting out of the branches of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">amim</fo:inline> and into the branch of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Avraham</fo:inline>. Hilchot Nedarim 9:23 and Yoma 66a implies that whenever
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Israel</fo:inline> is plainly mentioned, it is referring to
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">gerim</fo:inline>, <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>,
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">kohanim</fo:inline>, and <fo:inline font-style="italic">levi'im</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">8</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">8</fo:inline>Tehillim 16:5</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote>
		<fo:inline font-style="italic">Gerim</fo:inline> are the fourth house of <fo:inline font-style="italic">Yisrael</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">9</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">9</fo:inline>Sifrei Devarim 23:3 "The Kehilot"</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> may give the holiest of offerings; the burnt offering. The
		burnt offering is the only offering they may give as <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> proper.
		It appears to me, that this is because once <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> give a proper
		burnt offering, they enter a new status as a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline>, which is someone who
		is now sojourning into a relationship with <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> may or may not emanate from <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipot
			nogah</fo:inline>. If <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> keep the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot
			bnei Noach</fo:inline> for any other reason than for the sake of heaven, they emanate not
		from <fo:inline font-style="italic">klipot nogah</fo:inline>, but rather from the three impure
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">klipot</fo:inline> where no good exists. They then do not receive a portion in
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Olam haBah</fo:inline>. However, if <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> keep the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei Noach</fo:inline> for the sake of Heaven, they emanate from
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">klipot nogah</fo:inline> where there is good and evil. They do receive a
		portion in <fo:inline font-style="italic">Olam haBa</fo:inline>. One must be attached to the Source of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Olam haBa</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Bnei Noach</fo:inline> are made in the image of <fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem
			Elokim</fo:inline>:Tosephos YomTov on Avos 3:14 in explanation of the saying of Rabbi
		Akiva in the Mishna there "beloved is Man who is created in the Divine Image" as this was
		also said with reference to Bnai Noach - and according to what the Rambam writes in the Laws
		of Kings. See there.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Not only can <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Noach</fo:inline> do more<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">10</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space"><fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">10</fo:inline>Rambam, Hilchot Melachim 10:10</fo:block></fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote><fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">11</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space"><fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">11</fo:inline>A goy/a"kum/nochri is prohibited from orlah. However, if a nochri desires to observe the mitzvah of neta reva'i, it's laws apply to him and it is consecrated like neta reva'i of a Yisrael.
		- Rambam, Mishneh Torah, Neta Riva'i 10:10</fo:block></fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote>(although not mandatory),  <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
			Noach</fo:inline> are also halachically separate than the <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy
		stam</fo:inline>(plain goy)(Hilchot Melachim 10:10) who is an idolator(A"KUM)(Hilchot
		Ma'achalot Assurot 11:8). They are different <fo:inline font-style="italic">dea’ot</fo:inline> - containers of
		logic. It's clear in the juxtaposition from <fo:inline font-style="italic">Hilchot Melachim 10:10</fo:inline> that
		the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> and <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline> are two different types of entities.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">12</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">12</fo:inline>If a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> who observes the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei
					Noach</fo:inline> gives charity, we should accept it from him. It appears to me
				that it should be given to the Jewish poor for the ben Noach may derive his
				sustenance from the Jews and they are commanded to support him if necessary. In
				contrast, if a goy gives charity, we should accept it from him and give it to the
				goy poor." - Rambam, Hilchot Melachim 10:10 (from the Yemenite unedited)</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.minimum="0.5em" space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.maximum="2em" space-after.minimum="0.5em" space-after.optimum="1em" space-after.maximum="2em" keep-together.within-column="always" border-style="solid" border-width="1pt" border-color="black" background-color="#DDDDDD" padding-start="12pt" padding-end="12pt" padding-top="6pt" padding-bottom="6pt" margin-left="0pt" margin-right="0pt" id="d6e818"><fo:block/>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="0pt" space-before.minimum="0pt" space-before.maximum="0pt">Not only can bnei Noach do more, although not mandatory, bnei Noach are also
			halachically separate than the goy stam(plain goy) who is an idolator(A"KUM). They are
			different dea’ot.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">Every Jew in these times can teach the <fo:inline font-style="italic">sheva mitzvot bnei Noach</fo:inline>
		because Hilchot Melachim 8:10 says to.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">13</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">13</fo:inline><fo:inline font-style="italic">Likutei Sichos</fo:inline> Vol 26, 3rd <fo:inline font-style="italic">Parshas
				Yitro</fo:inline></fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote>It also says that every Jew should <fo:inline font-style="italic">lakuf</fo:inline>(strongly compel)
		non-Jews to keep the seven or kill the non-Jew if he doesn't. Therefore, the Jew has the
		ability in these times to determine who is the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> and who is the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline>. Therefore, <fo:inline font-style="italic">Hilchot Melachim</fo:inline> 10:10 applies
		in these times and a Jew can determine who the Jew has a <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvah
			l'hichuto</fo:inline> (to sustain the livelyhood, both spiritually and physically, in a
		time of need of the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> that gives
		<fo:inline font-style="italic">tzedekah</fo:inline>). This is the <fo:inline font-style="italic">k'ger toshav</fo:inline> of today. The
		Jew <fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvah l'hichuto</fo:inline> to sustain the <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline>
		that gives tzedekah and that <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> can do
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">mitzvot</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">14</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">14</fo:inline><fo:inline font-style="italic">Rambam, Hilchot Melachim</fo:inline> 10:10</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">A <fo:inline font-style="italic">ben Noach</fo:inline> can involve himself in any part of Torah(Chasam Sofer,
		Sheva Mitzvot haShem pg. 105)</fo:block>
