 Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block margin-left="0pt"><fo:block font-size="24.8832pt" font-weight="bold"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.optimum="10pt" space-before.minimum="10pt * 0.8" space-before.maximum="10pt * 1.2" hyphenate="false" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt" hyphenation-character="-" hyphenation-push-character-count="2" hyphenation-remain-character-count="2">Chapter 6. Sojourners</fo:block></fo:block><fo:block space-before="0.5em" font-style="italic" font-size="14.4pt" font-weight="bold">גרים - Gerim</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
	
	
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> is a sojourner. A <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> can be <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei
			Yisrael</fo:inline>
		<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">1</fo:inline>Bnei Yisrael are gerim to haShem - Rashi, Vayikra 24</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> or not.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">2</fo:inline>"I am a stranger and a sojourner with you: give me a possession of a buryingplace
				with you, that I may bury my dead out of my sight." - Genesis 23:4 KJV</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote> The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> without any other qualifier is almost always
		referring to <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline> in <fo:inline font-style="italic">halachah</fo:inline>.<fo:footnote><fo:inline><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline></fo:inline><fo:footnote-body font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="8pt" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" text-align="justify" start-indent="0pt" end-indent="0pt" text-indent="0pt" hyphenate="true" wrap-option="wrap" linefeed-treatment="treat-as-space">
			<fo:block><fo:inline font-family="Times New Roman, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-size="75%" font-weight="normal" font-style="normal" baseline-shift="super">3</fo:inline>Hilchot Assurot Machalot 11:8</fo:block>
		</fo:footnote-body></fo:footnote></fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> is anyone who attaches themselves to Godliness in some way
		and is not an idol-worshipper. This attachment could be by Torah, by interacting and
		clinging to <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>, or by contemplating on the true nature of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">haShem</fo:inline> and his wisdom. The <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> is a sojourner.
		He may or may not have the greatest of intentions.</fo:block>
	<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Ger</fo:inline> is often seen translated into English as the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">stranger</fo:inline>. In Torah, he is the <fo:inline font-style="italic">stranger</fo:inline> in the
		gate, the person that attaches himself to <fo:inline font-style="italic">bnei Yisrael</fo:inline>. However, this
		is not an accurate translation. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Stranger</fo:inline> in Hebrew is actually the
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">zer</fo:inline>. <fo:inline font-style="italic">Ger</fo:inline> is more accurately translated as
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">sojourner</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e992"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">History</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">History</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The first time we see <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> is in Genesis</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">The etymology of the word from the etymological dictionary.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e997"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Halacha</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Halacha</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">In <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah shebikhtav</fo:inline>, <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> usually refers to a
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline>. In <fo:inline font-style="italic">Torah shebe'alpeh</fo:inline>,
				<fo:inline font-style="italic">ger</fo:inline> usually refers a <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger tzedek</fo:inline>.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-style="italic">Gerim</fo:inline> are part of the congregation of
			<fo:inline font-style="italic">Yaacov</fo:inline>(Ramban on Deu 33:4 Moses commanded us a law, [even] the
			inheritance of the congregation of Jacob.)</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
	<fo:block id="d6e1009"><fo:block><fo:block><fo:block keep-together.within-column="always" margin-left="0pt" font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats"><fo:block keep-with-next.within-column="always"><fo:block font-family="Arial, Arial Unicode MS, Tahoma, Batang, sans-serif,Symbol,ZapfDingbats" font-weight="bold" keep-with-next.within-column="always" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.optimum="1.0em" space-before.maximum="1.2em" text-align="start" start-indent="0pt"><fo:marker marker-class-name="section.head.marker">Responsa</fo:marker><fo:block font-size="20.735999999999997pt">Responsa</fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block></fo:block>
		
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Statement:</fo:inline> The Ger Toshav doesn't exist today</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Statement:</fo:inline> A <fo:inline font-style="italic">ger toshav</fo:inline> is still
			a <fo:inline font-style="italic">goy</fo:inline></fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em"><fo:inline font-weight="bold">Response:</fo:inline> Hilchot Maachalot Assurot 11:8:"when we say
			plainly 'goy', we mean an idolator".Is Hilchot Maachalot Assurot 11:8 a true statement
			Jacob?The response you've made to my argument is an ad hominem(personal attack) and is
			not a valid argument; they are obfuscations. You also have yet to disprove any of the
			other arguments I've said. Concerning the Issurei Biah 14:7:You say that the ger toshav
			is a goy even after he swears off idolatry.Using that logic, when Issurei Biah 13:3 says
			a ger tzedek is a goy as well, you're still able to call him a goy:"When a goy desires
			to enter into the covenant..."However, a ger tzedek is no longer a goy, lest you say all
			converts cannot keep shabbat, study Torah, etc. per Hilchot Melachim 10:9 "A goy cannot
			study Torah...". Following the rule in set theory, a subset follows all the attributes
			of its superset, so when you call a ger a subset of goy, this cannot be the case.</fo:block>
		<fo:block space-before.optimum="1em" space-before.minimum="0.8em" space-before.maximum="1.2em">For instance:set all integers: {1,2,3,4,5,6,..}set even integers: {2,4,6,...}Set "even
			integers" being a subset of "all integers", and if "all integers" turn pink then "even
			integers" would turn pink due to inheritance by set theory. Therefore, ger toshav is not
			a subset of goy. Rather, a ger toshav(a non-idolator) is no longer a goy(idolator). They
			are not goy(idolator). They are ger(non-idolator).The only way(and I would agree with
			you) that gerim are subsets, is in the Torah definition of goy, such as bnei Yisrael
			being a goy kodesh(a holy nation). However, we're not talking in the written Torah term,
			but rather in the halachic term, as defined by the Rambam, Hilchot Maachalot Assurot
			11:8:"when we say plainly 'goy', we mean an idolator". Hilchot Maachalot Assurot 11:8 is
			true statement. If it is true, the you should read Issurei Biah 14:7 as:"Who is a ger
			toshav? This is an idolator which accepts upon himself to not serve idolatry, [along]
			with the other commandments commanded to the children of Noach"This also explains why
			rabbis refer to ger toshav as "half-converts"(as in Avodah Berurah, Avodah Zarah 64b).
			They were once idol-worshippers, who accepted not to be.You have not shown my argument
			to be invalid or false. Standing alone and apart from the rest of Mishneh Torah, your
			argument for Issurei Biah is valid(which would assume the Torah definition of goy), but
			coupled with the axiom of Maachalot Assurot 11:8(which assumes the halachic Rambam
			definition of goy), your argument is not valid.</fo:block>
	</fo:block>
